</DOCID>
<HL>
   Wendy's Chief Says
   Company to Perform
   `Much Better' in 1990
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WEN
</CO>
<IN>
RESTAURANTS, FAST-FOOD, CATERING (RES)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Wendy's International Inc. said its
restaurants are running better, its revamped menu is selling
better and its outlook is more optimistic than many analysts
think.
   Wendy's President and Chief Executive Officer James W.
Near said that analysts' second-quarter operating earnings
estimates of eight to 10 cents a share are "low" and that the
company will do "much better" in all of 1990 than last year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   April sales were very strong, Mr. Near said; the trend
seemed to continue into May.
   Rumors have circulated that Wendy's may be a candidate for
takeover-rumors that the company won't address.
   Today, Shearson Lehman Hutton raised its earnings estimate
to 35 cents a share for 1990, rating Wendy's as likely to
outperform the market by 10 to 20 percentage points.
   The fast-food industry is emerging from a period of
discounting that swallowed profits as restaurants offered
coupons and other inducements to diners. Wendy's problems
were compounded by financial difficulties at some franchises.
   Mr. Near says Wendy's expanded too rapidly through the
early and mid-1980s, selling franchises to owners who wanted
the investment and not the work. The company has been atoning
for those errors by buying back ailing franchises.
   While the company was able to show improved net income for
1989, thanks to a five cent-a-share gain from an accounting
change and a two cent gain from early extinguishment of debt,
operating results eroded from 1988. Wendy's net from
operations last year was $23.7 million, or 25 cents a share,
down from $28.5 million, or 30 cents a share, in 1988.
Revenue increased slightly to $1.07 billion, from $1.06
billion in 1988.
   Wendy's revenue fell in the first quarter of 1990 to
$241.3 million, from $259.5 million a year ago. Operating
profit increased to $3 million, from $814,000 in the 1989
first quarter. The 1990 quarter included a $499,000, or
one-cent-a-share, gain on extinguishment of debt for net
income of $3.5 million, or four cents a share. The 1989
quarter included $339,000 from extinguishment of debt and
$5.2 million, or six cents a share, from an accounting
adjustment for net income of $6.3 million, or seven cents a
share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900531-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bally Offers Exchange
   Of Over 20% Stake
   To Retire Junk Bonds
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   BLY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Bally Manufacturing Corp. offered to exchange a
more than 20% stake in the gambling and health-club concern
to retire a four-year-old, $135 million issue of junk bonds.
   The move is what Bally called a "first step" toward
shoring up its heavily leveraged balance sheet and improving
its stock price. Bally said it also is considering a variety
of asset sales, refinancings, joint ventures and other
measures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The bonds, sold through Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in
January 1986, have been trading at about 53 cents to 55 cents
on the dollar, Paul Johnson, Bally's chief financial officer,
said. Bally offered 57 shares of its common stock for each
$1,000 bond, or a total of about 7.7 million newly issued
shares if all the bonds are tendered. The company currently
has about 28 million shares outstanding.
   Bally's stock tumbled $1.50 yesterday on the news to close
at $10.625 in Big Board trading.
   Despite greatly increasingly the number of shares
outstanding, Bally said the equity-for-debt swap would
increase per-share profit by reducing the company's debt
load. The bonds, due January 2001, pay 13 5/8% interest, and
are the company's costliest debt.
   Bally had first-quarter profit of $7.6 million, or 21
cents a share, compared with $11.8 million, or 37 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue was $551.3 million compared
with $516.7 million. The company wouldn't project future 1990
results or say how much per-share net would be increased by
the exchange.
   In all, Bally has about $1.77 billion of long-term debt,
Mr. Johnson said, and its 1989 interest expense was $206
million. "The market perception is that we had too much
debt," he said.
   Bally joins some other junk-bond issuers in trying to buy
back its debt at a deep discount to the original price. Mr.
Johnson said, however, that since the company is under no
financial pressure to retire the bonds, it wouldn't sweeten
the offer. "It's terribly unlikely we would do anything
else," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0127
</DOCNO>
