900531-0127.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Suzuki Motor Co.:
   Annual Pretax Profit Rose
   76%; Cost Controls Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   J.SUZ
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Suzuki Motor Co. of Japan reported that consolidated
pretax profit for the year ended March 31 rose 76% to 25.48
billion yen ($168.7 million) from 14.48 billion yen a year
earlier, after the company limited growth in manufacturing
and administration costs.
   But net income fell 14% to 5.61 billion yen, or 13.75 yen
a share, from 6.54 billion yen, or 17.38 yen a share, because
of higher tax payments.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales of Suzuki vehicles and parts rose 2.3% to 982.57
billion yen from 960.49 billion yen. Costs increased only
0.4% for sales and 1.9% for administration, allowing
operating profit to surge from a year earlier. A Suzuki
official attributed the slower growth of costs to
exchange-rate factors, as well as changes in Japan's tax
system.
   Receipts from auto sales slipped 0.7% to 617.06 billion
yen from 621.66 billion yen. Motorcycle sales inched up 0.6%
to 148.266 billion yen from 147.384 billion yen. Parts sales
rose 13% to 217.247 billion yen from 191.45 billion yen.
Vehicle volume sagged in every area but sales of motorcycles
overseas; unit sales fell 2.2% for motorcycles and 6.6% for
autos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0126
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900531-0126.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Phoenix Technologies Ltd.:
   Phoenix Technologies Says
   14 Firms Licensed Software
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PTEC INTC NIPNY ALTO TAN
</CO>
<IN>
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Phoenix Technologies Ltd. said 14 personal computer makers
will license its EISA-standard system software, suggesting
new strength for the EISA computer communications standard
over International Business Machines Corp.'s MCA design.
   EISA, which stands for extended industry-standard
architecture, was developed last year by a group of PC makers
led by Compaq Computer Corp. to counter IBM's effort to push
a new standard that wasn't compatible with existing PCs. IBM
says its MCA -- or micro-channel architecture -- design
allows faster data exchange within and among its computers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a statement, Ron Fisher, president and chief executive
officer of the Norwood, Mass., company, said, "We continue to
see a groundswell of development activity on the EISA"
design. Phoenix, which sells system software that allows PC
makers to build IBM-compatible computers, said its EISA
products are made for PCs using Intel Corp. 80386 and 80486
chips.
   Companies licensing the EISA compatibility products from
Phoenix include Intel, NEC Corp., Tandy Corp. and Altos
Computer Systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
