<HL>
   Business Brief -- Agnico-Eagle Mines Ltd.:
   Shareholder to Ask Court
   To Block Planned Offering
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   AEAGF
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Agnico-Eagle Mines Ltd., Toronto, said it was notified
that one of its shareholders will seek a temporary court
injunction to block the gold mining company's planned
offering of 40 million Canadian dollars (US$33.9 million) in
common shares and share-purchase warrants.
   Application for the injunction will be made tomorrow in
Quebec Superior Court by Jacques Forget, who owns about 3% of
Agnico's shares, the company said. Agnico said Mr. Forget
also will seek a permanent injunction, on grounds concerning
the company's management, operations and policies. Mr.
Forget, who has said he plans to establish a group of holders
to pursue a takeover bid for Agnico, has accused the company
of "errors in management, which undermined shareholders'
equity and pushed down the share price."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Agnico said it will contest the injunction applications,
which it said are "totally without merit." The company said
it will proceed with its planned offering of shares and
warrants.
</TEXT>
