<HL>
   Your Money Matters:
   Beware of Accountants Promising Riches
   ----
   By Ellen E. Schultz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   It adds a whole new terror to taxes: Many financial scams
now involve accountants and tax preparers who select their
victims from among those whose returns they handle.
   In one such case, a jury in Dayton, Ohio, recently found
Naomi Taubman guilty of 60 counts of securities-law
violations in connection with the sale of "promissory notes"
to her tax clients. Victims testified that the 64-year-old
accountant told them they would receive returns as high as
24%, tax-free, says Richard Lipowicz, a prosecutor with the
fraud and economic-crimes division of the Montgomery County
prosecutor's office.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cases like this alarm securities regulators, who foresee
an increase in the number of complaints of fraud and abuse
involving accountants. The reason, they say, is that more and
more accountants are giving investment advice without, in
most cases, having to register as investment advisers.
   "They've got the books and records to know how much money
is there for the taking, and they have your trust," says
Scott Stapf of the North American Securities Administrators
Association. "That's a big leg up on ripping someone off."
   In the Taubman case, most of the victims were the
accountant's tax clients, says Mr. Lipowicz, assistant
prosecuting attorney. "She had prepared their tax returns --
in some cases for 40 years," he says. So when it came to
accepting investment advice, "they trusted her judgment
implicitly."
   Ms. Taubman's attorney, John H. Rion, says that his client
"merely borrowed money from clients and signed promissory
notes to secure those loans. We fully expect the case to be
reversed on appeal."
   Accounting-industry officials say that abuses by certified
public accountants aren't widespread. The cases that get
publicity typically involve financial advisers who take
custody of their clients' funds and sell investment products,
says John Hudson, director of accounting and consulting
services at the American Institute of Certified Public
Accountants. "These are not areas that most CPAs get involved
in," he says.
   Many cases of fraud involving accountants are Ponzi
schemes in which money from new investors is used to make
"interest" payments to those who invested earlier. Victims
are also often lulled by words such as "guaranteed,"
"insured," and "tax-free." As a result, they may not become
suspicious for months or years -- or until they try to get
their principal back.
   Typically, victims of these schemes are given bogus
debentures and promised returns in the 12% to 15% range.
   To get the money to "invest," they are frequently
encouraged to withdraw funds from individual retirement
accounts and other tax-deferred retirement plans, even though
this subjects their money to a 10% early withdrawal penalty
and taxes. In a recent case in Missouri, officials at the
state securities division allege, accountant Paul B. Brock
told clients his firm would pay the penalties for them. Mr.
Brock is currently awaiting trial on criminal charges in a
state court in Neosho, Mo. The public defender assigned to
the case had no comment.
   Investors are more vulnerable to fraud perpetrated by
their accountant because they know the person, securities
regulators say. They also say people are less suspicious of
investment advice proffered by an accountant -- particularly
when it includes tax strategies -- than they would be if it
came from a stockbroker or some other financial professional
who they figured was getting commissions for selling the
products being recommended.
   Consider the case of John Wyatt Duncan Jr., a 29-year-old
accountant sentenced to five to 15 years in prison in Kansas
after pleading guilty to several charges. According to the
arrest warrant issued for Mr. Duncan, one of his victims was
a widow with nine children whose tax returns he prepared.
   The warrant alleged that Mr. Duncan told her to withdraw
$203,238 from retirement accounts and mutual funds and put
all her money into something called "International
Investments." He told her the investment was fully insured
and would pay 12%, guaranteed for five years, the warrant
alleged. In fact, it said, the company didn't exist, and the
woman lost all her money.
   Other alleged victims included a couple who were told that
their IRAs needed to be rolled over into some other
tax-deferred program, a wheelchair-bound widow with a
maturing certificate of deposit, and a 17 year-old who had
received his father's death benefit. "This took away his
chance of a college education, and one retiree is now mowing
lawns to make ends meet," says Kansas Securities Commissioner
M. Douglas Mays.
   An attorney retained by Mr. Duncan had no comment.
   Accounting regulations vary from state to state, but only
a few states require accountants to register as investment
advisers -- and then only in some cases. Accountants are also
exempt from federal registration requirements for investment
advisers, as long as giving investment advice is incidental
to their practice.
   Various measures have been proposed to subject accountants
who give investment advice to greater regulation. A bill
introduced in Congress in March by Rep. Rick Boucher (D.,
Va.) would require accountants and others who receive
compensation as financial planners to register as investment
advisers.
   Accounting-industry officials say, however, that having
accountants register as investment advisers wouldn't curb
fraudulent or abusive behavior, but would leave accountants
open to more lawsuits. Consumers would be the ones to suffer
in the end, they say.
   "Qualified, competent, objective practitioners would be
deterred from giving financial planning advice because of the
specter of potential litigation," says William Goldberg,
chairman of personal financial planning legislation and
regulation subcommittee of the American Institute of
Certified Public Accountants.
   Whatever the case, an investor's best hope of avoiding
fraud, says securities regulators, is to "exercise the same
judgment you'd use with any investment adviser, such as a
financial planner or stockbroker," says Mr. Mays, the Kansas
regulator. "If you're suspicious, check with the securities
regulator in your state, or the state board of accountancy,
which will tell you whether they're certified and whether
they've had any complaints."
   ---
             Red Flags for Accounting Clients
                                                                                                       

   Spotting a crooked accountant or tax preparer can be
tough, but some things should make you suspicious. Think
about taking your business elsewhere if your accountant:
                                                                                                       

 -- Tells you to withdraw money from IRAs, 401(k)s, pension
plans and other tax-advantaged retirement accounts and put
all of it in another investment.
                                                                                                       

 -- Dangles an offer to get you into an investment with
above-market returns (say, 12% in the current environment),
especially if the investment is "tax-free."
                                                                                                       

 -- Urges you to put all of your money in a single
investment, particularly one that's supposedly "insured,"
"guaranteed" or "tax-free."
                                                                                                       

 -- Suggests driving you to the bank, meeting you there or
coming to your home to get the money for some hot investment
opportunity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0072
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900531-0072.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law -- Legal Beat:
   Caseloads of State Courts Soared in 1988
   ----
   By Edward Felsenthal and Wade Lambert
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B11
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR F.AQU FREST
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
INSURANCE (INS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   State courts, the workhorses of the nation's court system,
added an astonishing total of 98 million new cases to their
dockets in 1988, the most recent year for which data are
available.
   While 68 million involved traffic and ordinance
violations, more than 30 million were new civil, criminal and
juvenile cases, according to a study by the National Center
for State Courts in Williamsburg, Va.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In contrast, about 962,000 cases were brought into federal
courts last year, nearly 5% more than in 1988.
   State court civil filings in 1988 increased 4.3% from
1987, and new criminal cases rose more than 5%. The overall
increase in new filings is consistent with the steady growth
in state court caseloads since the center began the annual
study in 1984, says David Rottman, project director.
   Completion of cases filed in state courts in previous
years has not kept pace with new filings, the study shows.
The center estimates that the number of cases added to state
court dockets in 1988 exceeds the number of files closed by
about 5%.
   In the state trial courts that hear the most serious
felony and misdemeanor cases, filings of criminal cases rose
an unprecedented 8.4%, a rate which, if it continues, could
double the number of these cases every decade. Court experts
say the upsurge in state-level criminal cases is largely an
indication of a rise in drug-related prosecutions, which are
also clogging the federal courts.
   Defense lawyers, who have long complained about a
so-called litigation explosion, view the data as confirmation
that litigation is out of hand. Defense attorney James Morris
of the Richmond, Va., law firm Morris &amp; Morris says one
reason for court congestion is judges' willingness to admit
unreliable expert testimony. Many cases, he said, wouldn't
"even be filed if it weren't for the fact that some paid
expert loosely applying science is able to give an opinion"
that the plaintiff should recover.
   But the president of the mostly plaintiff-oriented
American Trial Lawyers Association played down the caseload
increase, saying it has generally kept pace with population
growth and has also reflected the rise in business failures.
The group's president, Russ Herman, said: "Even if all types
of litigation were increasing, in a democracy that's good.
The civil courts are the pressure valve for society."
   George Milko of HALT, a Washington organization that seeks
to promote the interests of consumers of legal services,
notes that the persistent rise in case filings provides
evidence that efforts to promote forms of dispute resolution
outside the court are not succeeding. "Maybe we ask our
courts to do more than they can handle," he says.
   ---
   RETIREE BENEFIT termination is halted by court restraining
order.
   A federal judge in Connecticut ordered the energy
conglomerate Societe Nationale Elf Aquitaine of Paris to
refrain temporarily from terminating a health benefits plan
for former senior executives of Texasgulf Inc., a U.S. oil
company acquired by the French company in 1981.
   Richard D. Mollison, who was chairman and chief executive
officer of Raleigh, N.C., company at the time of the
acquisition, sued Elf Aquitaine and its current chief
executive officer, Michel Schneider-Maunoury, after he
received a letter from Mr. Schneider-Maunoury that said the
plan would be abolished May 31, 1990.
   Marilyn Ford, a professor of law at the University of
Bridgeport in Connecticut, who represented Mr. Mollison,
asked the judge for a restraining order, arguing that the
takeover agreement guarantees continuation of the benefit
plan.
   The suit is part of a recent trend of cases against
companies that attempt to cut retirees' benefits in response
to rising health care costs. The case appears to be one of
the first in which a judge has put a restraining order on a
company before any termination of benefits.
   A spokesman for Elf Aquitaine said that the company
decided "to provide the same medical coverage for senior
officers as everybody else." He said although the takeover
agreement stipulates that employee benefit levels would not
be changed, the rising cost of health care has created a
definitional dispute over whether "level of benefits" implies
costs borne by the company or health services actually
received by retirees.
   Elf Aquitaine has retained the New York law firm Sullivan
&amp; Cromwell to represent it in the lawsuit. The judge
scheduled a hearing for June 1, when he will consider
granting a preliminary injunction, a stronger measure than
the restraining order he issued last week.
   Ms. Ford said that other former Texasgulf executives have
expressed interest in joining Mr. Mollison as plaintiffs in
the lawsuit and that there is potential for a class action
against the company.
   ---
   NEW YORK ELECTION law is challenged as unconstitutional in
federal suit.
   The lawsuit, filed by a group of labor unions, targets the
state's requirement that voters must register at least 60
days in advance to be able to vote in a primary election.
Deborah H. Karpatkin, an attorney for the unions and for 100%
Vote/Human Serve Campaign, a national group seeking to make
registration easier, said New York's 60-day cutoff "is one of
the longest, if not the longest," in the U.S.
   The suit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, claims the
requirement is unreasonable and detrimental to voter turnout.
"It places a harsh and unnecessary barrier in the way of
citizens' ability to participate in the political process. .
. . Many primary contests don't reach a high level of public
attention until the last few weeks before the election, when
it is too late to register for that primary," the suit said.
For the general election, the registration cutoff is 30 days
before the vote.
   A spokesman for the New York State Board of Elections said
the board and the state attorney general's office are
reviewing the suit. He said 60-day requirement is meant
mainly to deter "party raiding," in which a member of one
party tries to influence the opposing party's primary
results.
   For instance, a voter might register in the other party's
primary in an effort to get the other party's weaker
candidate into the general election, the spokesman said.
   ---
   CHINESE PROVINCE appoints U.S. lawyer as legal
representative.
   John T. Kesler, president of the 18-lawyer Salt Lake City
law firm of Woodbury, Jensen, Kesler &amp; Swinton, said he will
represent Szechwan province in business dealings and in legal
disputes between U.S. and Szechwan organizations. Szechwan
province has more than 105 million residents and is in
Western China. Many defense and aerospace companies are based
there.
   Woodbury Jensen specializes in international commercial
work, as well as real estate, technology and corporate law. A
visiting Chinese lawyer is an associate with the firm. The
firm has also established ties with four Chinese law firms in
different parts of China.
   Mr. Kesler received the appointment after lecturing in the
province's capital on international commercial law.
   ---
   SALARY FREEZE: Jones, Day, Reavis &amp; Pogue, one of the
nation's largest law firms, said it will keep starting
salaries this year at 1989 levels, ending years of annual
increases. In all its cities except New York, the
1,160-attorney firm will pay new lawyers, who arrive during
the summer and fall, a salary package worth $74,000. In New
York, the figure is $83,000. Michael H. Carpenter, the Jones
Day partner in charge of recruiting, said the Cleveland law
firm decided that "this was an appropriate year to hold the
line in terms of the concerns of our clients and in terms of
outside legal costs and in controlling those outside legal
costs." Jones Day's move could tempt other firms, many of
them hit hard by the current slowdown in corporate deal work,
to hold the line on salaries as well.
   ---
   ROSENMAN &amp; COLIN, New York, will merge its six-attorney
Washington office with Casson &amp; Harkins of Washington, whose
24 attorneys specialize in health care. "Rosenman had wanted
to increase its presence in Washington for some time," said
Casson &amp; Harkins's Joseph Casson, who said his own firm would
benefit from Rosenman's expertise in taxes and securities.
</TEXT>
