<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                          MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Port Authority of New York and New Jersey -- $201 million
special project bonds, Series 2, Continental Airlines Inc.
and Eastern Airlines Inc. LaGuardia Airport Passenger
Terminal Project, due Dec. 1, 2005, 2010 and 2015, repriced
by a Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co. group to lower yields by
12 to 13 basis points. The bonds are now priced to yield from
9.38% in 2005 to 9.63% in 2015, changed from priced to yield
from 9.50% in 2005 to 9.75% in 2015. There are now $51
million of 9% bonds priced at 96.96 to yield 9.38% in 2005,
changed from $50 million of 9% bonds priced at 95.98 to yield
9.50% in 2005. There are $30 million of 9% bonds priced at
95.52 to yield 9.50% in 2010, changed from $30 million of
9.13% bonds priced at 95.56 to yield 9.63% in 2010. There are
now $120 million of 9.13% bonds priced at 95.27 to yield
9.63% in 2015, changed from $130 million of 9 1/4% bonds
priced at 95.32 to yield 9.75% in 2015. Interest on the bonds
will be treated as a preference item in calculating the
federal alternative minimum tax that may be imposed on
certain investors. The bonds are not rated by Moody's
Investors Service Inc. or Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   Illinois Regional Transportation Authority -- $100 million
general obligation bonds, due Nov. 1, 1991-2005, 2010 and
2020, tentatively priced by a Bear Stearns &amp; Co. Inc. group
to yield from 6.10% in 1991 to 7.30% in 2010. Current
interest serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.10%
in 1991 to 7.20% in 2005. There are $16.64 million of 7.30%
term bonds priced at par in 2010 and $57.07 million of 7.20%
term bonds priced at 99 3/4 to yield 7.22% in 2020. The bonds
due in 2020 are noncallable. The bonds are AMBAC-insured and
rated Triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Arkansas Development Finance Authority -- $93.4 million
various single-family mortgage revenue bonds, 1990 Series A,
due Sept. 1, 2023 and current refunding bonds, Series B, due
Sept. 1, 2016, tentatively priced by a PaineWebber Inc. group
to yield 6.15% for Series B bonds due in 2016 and 6.35% for
Series A bonds due in 2023. The bonds have a mandatory put
date of March 1, 1991. Interest on the Series A bonds will be
treated as a preference item in caluculating the federal
Alternative Minimum Tax that may be imposed on certain
investors. The Series B bonds are not subject to the Federal
alternative minimum tax. A rating of SP1-plus is expected
from S&amp;P, according to an official with the lead underwriter.
A rating wasn't applied for from Moody's.
   Los Angeles Municipal Improvement Corp., Calif. -- $85
million leasehold revenue bonds, City of Los Angeles Central
Library Project, Series 1990 A, due June 1, 1994-2011, 2015
and 2020, apparently won by a Bank of America NT&amp;SA group.
The bonds, rated conditional-double-A by Moody's and
provisional-single-A-plus by S&amp;P, were priced to yield from
6.25% in 1994 to 7.25% in 2020. Current interest serial bonds
are priced to yield from 6.25% in 1994 to 7.15% in 2010 and
2011. There are $16.6 million of 7.10% term bonds priced at
98.85 to yield 7.20% in 2015. There are $28.67 million of
7.20% term bonds priced at 99.39 to yield 7.25% in 2020.
   Howard County, Md. -- Bulk of $55.6 million consolidated
public improvement bonds, 1990 Series A, due May 15,
1991-2010, and metropolitan district bonds, 1990 Series A,
due May 15, 1991-2020, were won by a Chase Securities Inc.
group. The $36.5 million consolidated public improvement
bonds, 1990 Series A, were priced to yield from 5.90% in 1991
to 7.00% in 2008-2010. The balance of the issue, $20 million
metropolitan district bonds, won by a Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. group. The bonds were priced to yield from 5.90% in 1991
to 7.10% in 2011 and 2012. Bonds due in 2013-2020 aren't
formallly reoffered. The bonds are rated doubleA-1 by Moody's
and double-A-plus by S&amp;P.
   New York State Dormitory Authority -- $51.6 million
revenue bonds, Fordham University issue, due July 1,
1994-2000, 2005 and 2015, were tentatively priced by a First
Boston Corp. group to yield from 6.40% in 1994 to 7.34% in
2015. Current interest serial bonds are priced at par to
yield from 6.40% in 1994 to 6.90% in 2000. There are $9.6
million of 7 1/4% term bonds priced at par in 2005 and $32.98
million of 7 1/4% term bonds priced at 99 to yield 7.34% in
2015. The bonds are AMBAC-insured and rated triple-A by
Moody's and S&amp;P.
   Birmingham Airport Authority, Ala. -- $50.1 million
airport revenue bonds, Series 1990 A and B, due July 1,
1994-2005, 2010 and 2020, tentatively priced by a Smith
Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co. Inc. group to yield from 6.30% for
non-AMT bonds due in 1994 to 7.52% for AMT bonds due in 2020.
Series A current interest serial bonds are priced at par to
yield from 6.50% in 1994 to 7.40% in 2005. There are $5.17
million of 7.40% term bonds priced at 99.25 to yield 7.46% in
2010. There are $17.19 million of 7.25% term bonds priced at
96.75 to yield 7.52% in 2020. Series B current interest
serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.30% in 1994 to
7.20% in 2005. There are $3.52 million of 7.20% term bonds
priced at 99.25 to yield 7.27% in 2010. There are $11.98
million term of 7.13% bonds priced at 97.75 to yield 7.31% in
2020. Interest on Series A bonds will be treated as a
preference item in calculating the federal alternative
minimum tax that may be imposed on certain investors. Series
B bonds aren't subject to the federal alternative minimum
tax. The bonds are AMBAC-insured and rated triple-A by both
Moody's and S&amp;P.
   University of California Regent's -- $50 million revenue
bonds, 1990 Seismic Safety Projects Issue, due Sept. 1,
19912005, 2010 and 2020, apparently won by a Dean Witter
