<HL>
   South Korea Current Account
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEOUL, South Korea -- The current account deficit for
South Korea narrowed to $171 million in April, the smallest
in four months. A year earlier there was a surplus of $516
million, according to the Bank of Korea.
   The April deficit -- the fourth-consecutive monthly
shortfall -- was attributed to sluggish merchandise exports
and expanding imports.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The central bank listed a cumulative current account
deficit for the first four months at $1.17 billion, compared
with the previous year's surplus of $1.86 billion.
   Citing a continued slowing in exports, bank officials said
the current account could register a deficit of $400 million
in May. Current account includes balances on payments for
trade in merchandise and services plus certain transfer
payments.
