900531-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Gorbachev, in a Significant Gesture,
   Plans to Meet South Korea's Roh in U.S.
   ----
   By Damon Darlin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   SEOUL, South Korea -- The U.S. arranged a last-minute
meeting between South Korean President Roh Tae Woo and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev. The meeting would be the most
significant gesture by the Soviets toward South Korea in more
than four decades.
   The meeting will take place in San Francisco Sunday, U.S.
officials confirmed, after Mr. Gorbachev finishes the
official phase of his summit meeting with President Bush in
Washington.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Seoul and Moscow don't have formal diplomatic ties and
Moscow maintains strong links with North Korea. But trade and
other business links between the South Koreans and the
Soviets have been strengthening. Topics would most likely
include South Korea asking Soviet help in diminishing the
antagonism between the South and the Communist North and
Soviet diplomatic recognition of Seoul.
   The U.S. involvement in setting up the meeting indicates
Washington's eagerness to defuse one of the world's last
trouble spots where U.S. troops face a Soviet-supported army.
About 42,000 U.S. troops are based in South Korea, many of
them at the Demilitarized Zone that divides the Korean
peninsula, eye-to-eye with North Korean troops.
   In Washington, a State Department spokeswoman said the
U.S. "would welcome a meeting" between the Soviet and South
Korean leaders, but she declined to answer questions about
such a meeting.
   The San Francisco meeting would be the first between a
Soviet leader and a high-level South Korean government
official, let alone a South Korean president. In addition to
seeking diplomatic recognition from the Soviets, Seoul wants
Moscow to let it join the United Nations. North Korea, which
also isn't a U.N. member, doesn't want South Korea to join
and has asked its allies -- China and the U.S.S.R. -- to veto
any admission attempt. Moscow, on the other hand, needs South
Korean trade and investment to help its struggling economy.
   Seoul has tried for many months to convince North Korea's
allies to recognize South Korea and to rein in North Korea,
whose excesses in past years have included bombing and
killing South Korean leaders in Rangoon and Burma, and
blowing up a Korean Air Lines commercial jet on the eve of
the 1988 Summer Olympics. Even before communism began
faltering in Eastern Europe last year, South Korea made
progress with many of those nations and was isolating North
Korea. Seoul established diplomatic ties with Poland, Hungary
and Czechoslovakia; in December, it and Moscow began limited
consular services in their trade offices in each other's
capitals.
   But Moscow, North Korea's main supporter, has held back on
full diplomatic ties. The Soviets very much want South
Korea's trade and economic assistance. China, which has
become more hard-line following the Tiananmen massacre last
summer, also shows little eagerness to openly support South
Korea over North Korea, though its trade relations with South
Korea have been growing rapidly, too.
   North Korea has always successfully played China off
against the Soviets and it has never been clear how much real
influence Moscow and Beijing have on North Korean leader Kim
Il Sung. North Korea has shown no sign of retreating from its
rigid Stalinist policies.
   The Gorbachev-Roh meeting could provide a major boost for
Mr. Roh, whose popularity is slipping as South Koreans blame
him for their economy's fits and starts. The Korean stock
market reversed its plummet Wednesday when rumors about the
trip circulated. It closed at 789.89, up 6.02 points.
   The trip will also undoubtedly feed criticism of Mr. Roh
and the U.S. by Korea's radicals, who are likely to contend
that the U.S. hand in setting up the Roh-Gorbachev meeting
proves their allegation that Mr. Roh is a puppet of the U.S.
   Mr. Roh originally planned to be in the U.S. during the
Gorbachev visit, but canceled his trip to Mexico, Canada and
the U.S. because he didn't want to risk being criticized for
leaving Korea when the country faced economic troubles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0044
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900531-0044.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   EC Study Finds
   Fraud, Waste
   In Farm Policy
   ---
   Court of Auditors Criticizes
   EC Commission, States
   For Roles in Program
   ----
   By Mark M. Nelson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- In a devastating condemnation of the European
Community's agricultural policy, the EC's Court of Auditors
found widespread criminal fraud, mismanagement and waste in
its $33 billion-a-year farm-subsidy program.
   The court criticized the EC member states and the EC
Commission for their roles in managing farm policy. The court
said member states provided too few safeguards against
financial abuse and that the commission had failed to satisfy
"the requirements of public accountability."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John Carey, one of the court's 12 members, said he
couldn't estimate how much money the EC was losing to fraud
and mismanagement. Previous estimates from other sources have
ranged between $3 billion and $10 billion a year. But Mr.
Carey said court investigators had uncovered a series of
multimillion-dollar cases in the past two years including
rigged tendering of contracts, subsidies paid on
misidentified or nonexistent products and other abuses. He
also said the EC's policy was too complex and difficult to
administer.
   Guy Legras, the commission's top civil servant in charge
of agriculture, defended the EC's farm policy and the
commission's management of it. He said many of the cases the
court uncovered were blown out of proportion. But the
criticism of the EC farm policy comes at an awkward time for
the commission; it is trying to defend its agriculture policy
in world trade talks and at the same time convince member
states to give more powers to EC institutions.
   This isn't the first time the court has faulted EC farm
policy, but the strong language of the report is likely to
get more attention than previous investigations. A U.S. trade
official said she hoped the Court of Auditors report "would
finally wake EC consumers up to the fact that they are paying
through the nose" for a program that is supposed to be
helping farmers but instead is lining the pockets of big
traders, shippers and other middlemen.
   The court's findings also could make it more difficult for
the EC to defend its agricultural subsidies program in the
current Uruguay Round of world trade talks. In those talks,
the EC's export-restitution program is blamed by most other
countries for raising retail food prices and creating unfair
competition. Experts say the policy is unfair to producers
from less-developed countries who are often squeezed out of
the market by the subsidized European products.
   The independent Court of Auditors is charged with
overseeing financial management of the EC budget, about 54%
of which is composed of the agricultural subsidy program. The
latest investigation covered only beef, dairy and grain
exports. The total export subsidies program costs EC
taxpayers more than $11.5 billion a year.
   ---
   Martin du Bois contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
