<HL>
   Boesky Ex-Aide Testifies He Conducted
   Illegal Trades With John Mulheren
   ----
   By Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A key aide to convicted former stock
speculator Ivan F. Boesky said that he conducted numerous
illegal securities trades with defendant John A. Mulheren Jr.
and that Mr. Mulheren proposed a bogus scheme to compensate
Mr. Boesky for profits on those trades.
   Michael Davidoff's testimony provided the most damaging
evidence yet in the government's case against Mr. Mulheren,
former chief of Jamie Securities Co. Mr. Davidoff appeared to
help the government much more than did his former boss, Mr.
Boesky, who testified last week.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Mulheren is charged with 41 counts of conspiracy,
securities fraud and keeping false records in connection with
his dealings with Mr. Boesky.
   Appearing nervous and speaking with a slight stammer, Mr.
Davidoff recalled a series of trades with Mr. Mulheren that
Mr. Davidoff said were designed to generate tax losses for
Mr. Boesky's trading company and to help evade net capital
requirements.
   Mr. Davidoff, 46 years old, said the trades with Mr.
Mulheren, which Mr. Davidoff said he believed to be illegal
at the time he did them, began in July 1985 and continued
until March of the following year. Mr. Davidoff said he
conducted the trades at Mr. Boesky's direction. Mr. Davidoff,
once Mr. Boesky's chief trader, pleaded guilty in 1987 to one
felony count related to securities fraud and is awaiting
sentencing.
   In every case, Mr. Davidoff said, Mr. Boesky's company
agreed to sell securities to Mr. Mulheren's firm with the
understanding that those securities would later be
repurchased. Mr. Davidoff said he repeatedly assured Mr.
Mulheren that all profits and losses from the trades "would
be borne by" Mr. Boesky's company.
   Mr. Davidoff said the first of these trades with Mr.
Mulheren involved stock of Unocal Corp. and was arranged by
Mr. Boesky himself. Mr. Davidoff said he did the trade with
Mr. Boesky after talking with him. Shown records of the trade
by assistant U.S. attorney Alfred Pavlis, Mr. Davidoff
acknowledged it was his handwriting on the documents.
   Mr. Davidoff said that Mr. Mulheren later agreed to buy
securities in five other companies with the understanding
Jamie Securities would sell these securities back to Mr.
Boesky at a later date and be compensated for any losses. By
December 1985, Mr. Davidoff said, Jamie Securities owed Mr.
Boesky's firm "over $1 million" from profits that Jamie made
on the trades.
   According to Mr. Davidoff's testimony, Mr. Mulheren
proposed a scheme where Jamie would inflate brokerage bills
it paid to Mr. Boesky's trading company in late 1985. But in
March 1986, when Mr. Boesky wanted to speed up the payments,
Mr. Davidoff said that he agreed with Mr. Mulheren that Jamie
would sell Mr. Boesky securities at below-market prices,
resulting in a profit to Mr. Boesky.
   Mr. Davidoff is expected to continue his testimony today
and will likely be cross-examined by Thomas Puccio, an
attorney for Mr. Mulheren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900531-0039
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900531-0039.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   American International Seeks to Acquire
   Fischbach Through $44 Million Merger
   ----
   By Martha Brannigan and Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   AIG FIS APL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   American International Group Inc., in an apparent move to
protect itself from potentially large performance-bond
claims, said it is proposing through a subsidiary to acquire
Fischbach Corp. in a merger at $11 a share, or approximately
$44 million.
   American International, a large New York-based insurer, is
responsible for a large portion of the performance bonds for
Fischbach, a troubled electrical and mechanical contracting
concern based in New York. While an American International
spokesman said he couldn't estimate the dollar amount of the
performance bonds issued to Fischbach, the total reportedly
is about $600 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Performance or surety bonds usually guarantee that
construction projects for municipalities and other entities
are completed as promised.
   American International officials weren't available late
yesterday to explain the status of the work guaranteed by
these bonds and how recent these commitments were.
   American International also said it plans to bring in a
construction company to provide management consulting
services to loss-ridden Fischbach as soon as American
International can obtain approval from Fischbach's board.
   In addition, APL Corp., controlled by Miami financier
Victor Posner, said it and American International modified
the terms of American International's previously announced
option to acquire APL's approximately 54% stake in Fischbach
to set a new exercise price of $11 a share.
   APL also said it agreed to recommend approval of the
merger proposal to Fischbach's board, which APL said is
planning to meet next week to consider the matter.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Fischbach closed at $9.75, unchanged. Fischbach officials
couldn't be reached for comment.
   American International said the proposed merger would be
subject to approval of Fischbach's board and other customary
conditions.
   Mr. Posner couldn't be reached for comment, but he may rue
the day he became involved with Fischbach. He paid far more
for the shares than the $11-a-share option he gave to
American International. And the manner in which he acquired
control has proven to be part of one of Wall Street's most
high-profile scandals.
   According to testimony by Michael Milken, the former
junk-bond king who pleaded guilty last month to six felonies,
one of his misdeeds was forcing an unwilling Fischbach into
the hands of Mr. Posner by having Ivan Boesky take a large
and unlawfully secret position in the company's stock.
   Analysts were puzzled by American International's
announcement yesterday. One said that if a contractor can't
complete a job, insurers would typically pay the claims, but
not take over the entire contracting company.
   Another person familiar with Fischbach believes American
International's move is "purely defensive," as the insurer
would probably like to oversee the management of Fischbach as
a way of guarding against possible future claims against its
performance bonds.
   In an interview with The Wall Street Journal last
December, Maurice Greenberg, chairman of American
International, said the company has been an insurer of
"Posner enterprises for a number of years and with
satisfactory results."
   Mr. Greenberg also said last December that American
International could hold on to Fischbach as an investment or
act "as a facilitator," possibly selling it to another entity
that would be interested in the contracting business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
