<HL>
   Business Brief -- Webcott Holdings:
   Resolution on Del Webb's
   Takeover Plan Is Approved
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WBB
</CO>
<LP>
   Webcott Holdings, holder of a 9.7% stake in Del Webb
Corp., said its nonbinding shareholder resolution to remove
Del Webb's anti-takeover provisions was approved by more than
78% of the holders who voted on the proposal, according to an
official tally.
   The votes in favor of the proposal represented a majority
of the company's shares outstanding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Del Webb, a Phoenix, Ariz., real estate development
concern, had said last week that a preliminary report of
inspectors of election for its May 16 annual meeting
indicated that the resolution had passed.
   The resolution by Los Angeles-based Webcott, controlled by
Del Webb director James L. Cotter, requested that the board
redeem shareholder rights issued under a so-called "poison
pill" plan adopted last year. In April, Del Webb agreed to
several of Mr. Cotter's demands to avert a proxy fight at the
annual meeting. A poison pill plan is aimed at making hostile
takeovers prohibitively expensive.
   A special committee of the company's board will consider
options and make a report to the board regarding the
nonbinding resolution.
</TEXT>
