<HL>
   Who's News:
   Blackstone Group
   Hires Richard Ravitch
   As a General Partner
</HL>
<DATE>
05/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Blackstone Group said Richard Ravitch, the
former public official and turnaround specialist who ran
unsuccessfully for mayor of New York in 1989, will join the
investment boutique as a general partner.
   Mr. Ravitch, who will start work tomorrow, said he will
focus mainly on restructuring over-leveraged companies -- "of
which there will be many in the 1990s" -- and on
recapitalizing troubled thrifts and other financial
institutions. He also said he will scout out prospects for
Blackstone's $800 million buy-out and investment fund.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Everything he does will be tied in some way to his past
experience and background," said Jerome Traum, a Blackstone
general partner.
   Mr. Ravitch, 56 years old, is known mainly for his
chairmanship during the mid-1970s of the New York State Urban
Development Corporation, which he is credited with saving
from bankruptcy; and for heading the New York State
Metropolitan Transit Authority, which he saw through a bitter
transit strike in 1980 and spent until 1984 rebuilding with
bond issues and innovative financing.
   His bailout plan for the UDC became the model for the
Municipal Assistance Corporation, created in 1975 to help New
York City out of its fiscal crisis.
   Mr. Ravitch has also served as chairman of HRH
Construction, a developer of several major New York office
buildings and residential projects. In 1985 he led a group of
investors who bought, ran and resold in 1988 -- at a big
profit -- New York's Bowery Savings Bank. "That's one of the
most successful turnarounds that has ever taken place," said
Mr. Traum.
   Since 1989, Mr. Ravitch has concentrated on writing,
teaching at New York University and seeking new opportunities
in business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
